Press 1 to save as a jpeg.

metadata.name: Endless Drawing #47
metadata.description:
Generator of virtually infinite drawings based on epicyclic motions. 
 
A polyline of three or more segments rotates around a predefined center, progressively changing its configuration. The center of rotation is located at the top outside the display area. The changes are made by rotating the first segment around the center and subsequent segments around the end vertex of the previous one. The segments from the second onward are drawn at each frame, and all traces are then moved down.

Depending on the lengths of the segments and the individual rotation speeds, the drawings can repeat in the same exact way after a few minutes or after very many years.
 
Antonio Belluscio (@livinbits)
November 2021

Viewing in live mode on smartphones or in portrait format windows is recommended.
With a click or tap, you can increase/decrease the scrolling speed.

metadata.description:
Medusa is a generative piece playing with noise, cosinus/sinus functions and lines.  The radius, frequency and amplitude of each lines are generated for each token, along with the color theme and the lines's count. Some rare items are available.

metadata.name: Earth #74
metadata.description:
This artwork builds upon the annual Earth Day animations I’ve been making since 2009. The particle system was written from scratch in vanilla javascript (a single 22KB HTML/JS file). The particles are constrained to the surface of a sphere and exhibit "social interactions" from which life-like patterns emerge.

Each animation will be minted with a randomly assigned color palette, energy level, particle type, and social behavior. Over 900 basic phenotypes are possible, with countless subtleties expressed per phenotype. There are a few wild rarities waiting to be born as well...

This work evolved over a three day creative sprint with fellow algorithmic artist Canton Becker. We think the Earth deserves a blockchain that doesn't blow tons of carbon. This animation pays tribute to the climate scientists and tech innovators who are working to secure our future on this planet. To that end, 10% of all proceeds from this project will be donated to The Coalition for Rainforest Nations.

metadata.name: Aluna #119
metadata.description:
Aluna is the insistence that the world is made and shaped through ideas as well as processes. The series is inspired by the human-led speciation of plants such as orchids and irises, and animals such as goldfish and betta fish - whose features are often exaggerated. Not all speciation is towards ornament - our ancestors developed foods and natural materials through years of selection and hybridization, and this is continued today helping discover new resilient forms. Our ability to imagine and reshape living organisms as well as entire ecosystems is brought into focus through climate change. 

The name Aluna is based on the philosophy of the Tairona people of Colombia, survived through present-day descendants. This Andean philosophy maintains a fundamentally different perspective about the role of humans - occupied with the imagining, enhancement, and nurturing of life.
